<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-169-060 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 718 195</DOCID><JOURNAL>UNIX World  May 1991 v8 n5 pS21(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Barriers to change. (selling Unix in the Soviet Union)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mufford, Caroline.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The outlook for selling Unix to the Soviet Union in the nearfuture remains bleak because of a lack of hard currency and aninflux of inexpensive microcomputers.andP;  Many observers say there isno chance of Western Unix vendors making money in the SovietUnion, although some say that Unix will spread out quickly becausethe Soviets will be able to import the Western Unix applicationbase.andP;  HP and others have been trying unsuccessfully to sell Unixmachines to the Soviets; software vendors have even greaterdifficulty because Soviets frequently copy software.andP;  Those whoare optimistic about market prospects say the Soviets wantreal-time UNIX applications for modernizing research anddevelopment organizations.andP;  Soviet isolationism has resulted in asevere shortage of hard currency; the private and industrialsectors have little access to it.andP;  Cultural barriers includewidespread software copying and gaps between assumptions andrealities.andP;  Education is the key to promoting Unix in the SovietUnion, observers agree.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     UNIXMarket EntryMarket PenetrationOutlookSoviet UnionInternational TradeComputer Industry.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>